Seaborn Library:¶

Seaborn is a Python visualization library based on matplotlib. It provides a high-level interface for drawing attractive statistical graphics

IRIS Dataset:¶

The data set consists of 50 samples from each of three species of Iris (Iris setosa, Iris virginica and Iris versicolor). Four features were measured from each sample: the length and the width of the sepals and petals, in centimetres.

Pairwise Plotting¶

Compare one independent variable with many dependent variables

In [23]:
iris = sns.load_dataset("iris")
g = sns.PairGrid(iris)
g = g.map(plt.scatter)
sns.plt.show()
In [24]:
g = sns.PairGrid(iris)
g = g.map_diag(plt.hist)
g = g.map_offdiag(plt.scatter)
sns.plt.show()
In [25]:
g = sns.PairGrid(iris, hue="species")
g = g.map_diag(plt.hist)
g = g.map_offdiag(plt.scatter)
g = g.add_legend()
sns.plt.show()

Kernel Density Estimation¶

  • Kernel density estimation is typically known as its short form kde
  • kernel density estimation is also known as the Parzen-Rosenblatt window method
  • Its a non-parametric way to estimate the probability density function (pdf) for a variable (x)
    • Data is not required to fit normal distribution (fewer assumptions)
    • Mostly data is ordinal, does not rely on numbers but is ranking or order of sorts
In [29]:
g = sns.PairGrid(iris, hue='species')
g = g.map_upper(plt.scatter)
g = g.map_lower(sns.kdeplot, cmap="Blues_d")
#g = g.map_diag(sns.kdeplot)
g = g.map_diag(plt.hist)
sns.plt.show()
In [7]:
# Create a Pairplot
g = sns.pairplot(iris,hue="species",palette="muted",size=5,
    vars=["sepal_width", "sepal_length"],kind='reg',markers=['o','x','+'])

# To change the size of the scatterpoints in graph
g = g.map_offdiag(plt.scatter,  s=35,alpha=0.5)

# Additional line to adjust some appearance issue
plt.subplots_adjust(top=0.9)
g.fig.suptitle('Relation between Sepal Width and Sepal Length',
    fontsize=34,color="b",alpha=0.3)
sns.plt.show()
